    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><div align="center">
        <p>Planning Promotions </p>
        <p align="left">As with most things, designing and running a promotion takes planning and preparation. It is not something that you can just &quot;put together&quot; and hope it comes off well. Shari's has developed a Holiday and Chalkboard Specials binder to assist the management staff with this task. It is important to establish a budget before you begin planning a promotion so that you know what your limitations are. Some things to consider when planning  promotions are:</p>
        <p align="left"><u>Guest Involvement or Contest</u>: Decide if you are going to involve the guest in the promotion in some way. Are they going to fill out trivia sheets on Shari's anniversary, will they enter a drawing for a prize, bring in a coupon or sing for their free coffee? If you decide to involve the guest make sure that your activity is appropriate and that you prepare your employees well. They will most likely be the person who explains to the guests. Try to be creative, guest involvement can be fun when well thought out and planned. </p>
        <p align="left"><u>Employee Involvement or Contest</u>: Decide if you will have something special for your employees during the promotion. You can run a contest or simply focus on excellent guest service - for example, pass out Shari's bucks when you &quot;catch&quot; employees giving exceptional service. Buy small prizes that they can purchase with their Shari's bucks. Also think of ways to create interaction between the guest and employees to build customer relations. For example, you may have something that the employees can give to the guests for participating. Again, planning in advance is a key.</p>
        <p align="left"><u>Advertising</u>: There are several ways that you can advertise. Local papers are usually affordable - just make sure that you have your DM's approval. You can also advertise in the store a week or two before the event using flyers, the chalkboard and word-of-mouth from your employees. You may also want to partner with fellow merchants who may help you by advertising to their guests. </p>
        <p align="left">Decorations: There are many ways that you can decorate the restaurant for not a lot of expense. Consider:</p>
        <div align="left">
          <ul>
            <li>Interior -Balloons, streamers, and holiday cutouts are all inexpensive and some can be saved from year to year. Make sure that decorations don't interfere with the work flow, are not offensive (Halloween can sometimes cause problems) and that they are colorful and cheery.</li>
            <li>Pie Case: Don't forget the pie case, it is one of the biggest display tools that you have. </li>
            <li>Uniforms: You may want to allow the staff to support the promotion by wearing a different uniform for the day. For example: a football jersey on Super bowl day or Hawaiian shirts for a summer promotion.</li>
            <li>Plates: It is also possible to decorate the plates. For example, you might use a small flag on a toothpick to decorate all plates on the Fourth of July.</li>
            </ul>
          <blockquote>
            <p>&nbsp;</p>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2"><p>Meal Specials: You will want to have a meal special for most holiday promotions. Here are some things to consider when planning the menu.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Think of the Season: During the winter holidays, guests are more willing to eat rich heavy specials like meat dishes but during the summer fish and salads go better.</li>
          <li> Will it Conflict: Think about what is on special right now. You don't want to run an inexpensive dish-up special against a $10.99 table tent steak promotion, it will hurt your PPE. You might consider combining items for value and a high ticket average, for example, dinner including dessert.</li>
          <li>Consider Your Cook Staff: Are they newer and less experienced?A complicated special may actually hurt your store if they get overwhelmed. On the other hand, if you have experienced cooks, they may enjoy helping you plan  specials.</li>
          <li>Consider the Ingredients Used: Are they all in-house? We have a large inventory of various products on hand. Think of the walk-in, freezer and storeroom as your grocery store. Be creative, remember our regular guests are looking for something new.</li>
          <li>Plan to Run Out: It is OK to run out of a special. That simply means that it was successful. Try not to have a lot left over that you will have to figure out what to do with.</li>
      </ul></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td valign="middle"><p align="center" class="style1">Click the icon for instructions on costing out a special!</p>
      <p align="center"><a href="costing_out_a_special.htm" target="_blank"><img src="../../../images/money_goes.gif" alt="" width="69" height="88" border="0"></a> </p></td>
      <td><div align="center">
        <p>Planning a Menu </p>
        <p align="left">After you have decided what menu items you will be featuring you will need to:</p>
        <div align="left">
          <ul>
            <li>Cost out each special</li>
            <li>Design the plate arrangement</li>
            <li>Test cook the special</li>
            <li>Have the staff taste and describe the special</li>
            <li>Place the special on the chalk board</li>
            <li>Enter the special into the POS system (refer to your POS manual) </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div></td>
