    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle"><div align="center">Holidays and Events</div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td valign="middle"><p align="center"><a href="popular_holidays.htm" target="_blank"><img src="../../../images/party.gif" width="101" height="116" border="0"></a></p>      </td>
      <td>What are the most popular holidays or events? It only makes sense to make these days special. <span class="style1">Click on the birthday boy to learn more about holidays. </span></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle"><p>Holidays and events can be broken down into three categories: national holidays, such as Christmas, personal celebrations such as birthdays and anniversaries and local promotions such as a community parade or mall sale. </p>
      <p><u>National Holidays</u>: The corporate Research and Development department will provide promotions for some holidays, but typically it is left to the management staff to develop or augment holiday promotions. Usually, these types of holidays will not be promoted with advertising, we are basically trying to provide a festive occasion and variety for our regular guests. Typically, our guests are not looking for a bargain on these  holidays - so keep that in mind when you are decided on specials to run. Also consider that these days are busier than normal so make sure that your special don't hamper the flow of service - high-ticket simple specials are best.</p>
      <p><u>Personal Celebrations</u>: Were you surprised to find that the number one event celebrated in restaurants was birthdays? Since this is true wouldn't it be wise for each restaurant to have a standard way to celebrate a guest's birthday. Typically, everyone disappears so they don't have to sing! It would be a great store project to involve the crew and come up with a unique way to celebrate birthdays: a unique birthday song, a stock of cards the crew could sign, or a special dessert or birthday hat. These are the types of things a guest remembers that influences their daily dining decision.</p>
      <p><u>Local Events</u>: Local promotions are a great way to receive some extra guest traffic at little or no cost. Try to develop a promotion that fits the theme of the celebration using the Planning Promotions list above. A common mistake made by managers during this type of promotion is under-staffing. It is truly a shame to bring in new guests only to disappoint them with poor service or food quality. </p></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle">&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle"><div align="center">
        <p>Community Involvement<br>
          <br>
          </p>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td valign="middle"><div align="center"><img src="../../../images/little_league.gif" width="81" height="149"></div></td>
      <td valign="middle"><u>Sponsorships</u>: You will receive many requests for sponsorships of local sports teams, school clubs and events. Outright donations are handled by our marketing department and you should refer any such requests to them. Request for prizes can be handled by the management staff. You should review each request and determine if it will benefit your restaurant or standing in the local community. <br></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle"><u>Cross Promotions</u>: Cross promotions are partnerships with other local businesses - they give you something, you give them something. This is a great way to aquire gifts and rewards to give to your staff for in-store contests or recognition. For example, you may trade a dinner for two for free movie rentals from the local video store. Cross promotions may also involve mutual advertising for non-competing businesses (those that don't sell food).<br>
      <br>
      <u>Community Presence</u>: Developing a community presence is getting your name and face recognized in your area. This can take time but can reap great results. Perhaps you can start by taking a pie to the bank the next time you make a deposit, introducing yourself to one business owner a week, or joining your mall association or local chamber of commerce.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle">&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle"><div align="center">Guest/Employee Interaction (Fun) <br>
        <br>
      </div></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td valign="middle"><img src="../../../images/happy_faces.JPG" width="201" height="160" border="1"></td>
      <td valign="middle">These types of promotions are designed to build employee moral or guest loyalty. You are trying to build a sense of belonging and community. These can be simple things such as bringing in cookies for the crew or having the crew bring in baby pictures and guessing who each one is. They can also involve sales and performance goals. For example: you might try to beat the store's highest sales record for Christmas or lower food cost for a period. All of these types of promotions help the employees feel a as though they are a part of the restaurant and valued for their contribution. </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle">Fun promotions can also involve the guests in such activities as playing Shari's trivia, voting on a favorite pie type or singing their favorite Elvis song on Elvis' birthday. </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td colspan="2" valign="middle"><br>
        As you can see, promotions can be simple or involved but all take a lot of planning. Some managers may question if it is worth it - and that is a good question with no black and white answer. In some cases, the results can be easy to see, for example: we sold X number of specials at a certain price or increased sales or guest counts over last week or last year. Sometimes, results are a little harder to determine. For example: what is one guest worth who has a great experience on their birthday and comes in more often and brings other people? What is a positive employee attitude worth? All are interesting questions that you should consider when you are deciding upon the goals and worth of your in-store promotions.</td>
    </tr>
